<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837889500025&r=1&w=2">The correct way to signify no-such-host</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000011&r=1&w=2">David C. Plummer &lt;DCP () QUABBIN ! SCRC ! Symbolics ! COM&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198711">1987-11-19 14:09:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781927028&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781927028&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

What is the correct way to declare that there is no such host for a
given domain name?  For example, the MIT.EDU name
 - does exist (other things are under it) so it doesn't generate NAME-ERROR.
 - does not have an IN HINFO RR.
	Real hosts may not have HINFO records.  It's probably a mistake,
	but there's no domain-reason that I know of why hosts are
	required to have them.
 - does not have any IN A RRs.
	Real hosts may have addresses not on the Internet.
Given that I don't get a NAME-ERROR, what's the right algorithm?

PS, MIT.EDU doesn't have an IN MX record either, so what algorithm
should mailers use to determine that it can't send there, considering no
NAME-ERROR is generated?

